00:07:01.910 --> 00:07:05.200
So after my meeting with
Fred Rogers in the elevator,

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:06.850
I went by his office.

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:09.190
And we started talking
about what we could do.

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:11.310
I was an educator,
there as director

00:07:11.310 --> 00:07:13.010
of educational services.

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:16.620
And he said, I wish
we could do more

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:20.870
to help people-- parents,
caregivers, preschool teachers,

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:23.940
whoever's using it-- help
them understand that there are

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:27.610
some lessons, not just watch
the show, but something to do.

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:32.310
So we set about developing what
we call the plan and play book.

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:36.480
I was watching the shows
then writing lesson plans

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:39.490
for what to do after
you watch the show.

00:07:39.490 --> 00:07:44.530
And that book became sort of the
basis for Public Television's

00:07:44.530 --> 00:07:48.240
Ready to Learn Project,
and started a relationship

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:51.300
with Fred and his
company, including

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:58.790
David, that has gone on since
the late '60s, '70s, and exists

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:04.540
even today where I'm still
involved with the Fred Rogers

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:07.560
company, and with the
Fred Rogers memorial

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:10.790
scholarship, which is
our effort to continue

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:13.140
with his legacy in
children's media.

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:20.060
Who was Fred Rogers?

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:22.830
How many of you think you
know how Fred Rogers was?

00:08:22.830 --> 00:08:25.390
What a unique person he was.

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:28.910
Do you know that
he was a puppeteer?

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:30.270
