So we set about-- I was
one of the producers

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:38.270
of that show--
putting this together.

00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:41.540
And in doing so, I was
re-reading Fred's materials,

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:44.350
looking at the shows, and I
kept coming home and telling

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:47.350
my husband, who was a professor
of management organizational

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:53.430
behavior, much of what goes into
making organizations work until

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:56.000
he said--

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.780
IAN MITROFF: When Donn a
was sharing the lessons,

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:00.580
the lessons were more
profound than you

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:01.920
get in most management books.

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:04.960
I mean, they're not devoid
of lessons, but they're dry.

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:06.430
They're didactic.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:09.460
And the idea that
took shape for Donna

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:11.880
and I is that we began
to go back and read

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.310
some of the major
fables the were

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:16.060
on the Neighborhood
of Make Believe.

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:18.030
And the idea that
crystallized is

00:13:18.030 --> 00:13:21.740
that the fables were in effect
little mini business cases.

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:24.630
That King Friday, for
example, is the autocratic CEO

00:13:24.630 --> 00:13:27.400
and you can begin to identify
the other characters.

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:30.800
And the idea said, Look
let's try and teach

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:33.710
organizational behavior
through fables and stories.

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:34.970
Why fables and stories?

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:38.040
Because that's the primary
way that human beings

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:39.560
have communicated
with one another

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:42.750
since the dawn of civilization,
not with formulas,

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:45.600
not with textbooks,
but with good stories.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:49.000
We were lucky to get to Palgrave
McMillan-- the next slide.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.220
DONNA MITROFF: But wait I
want to have the next slide.

00:13:50.220 --> 00:13:51.678
IAN MITROFF: We
were lucky to get--

00:13:51.678 --> 00:13:53.640
DONNA MITROFF: A
contributer to this idea

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:56.870
that there are lessons
here for grownups

00:13:56.870 --> 00:13:59.260
was at this tribute
to Fred Rogers.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:02.690
One of the people who
spoke was Anne Sweeney.

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:05.430
Some of you might have heard--
Anne was here recently doing

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:11.340
a talk to women's leadership
in Silicon Valley.

00:14:11.340 --> 00:14:14.210
And you see she's got a
very high level position.

00:14:14.210 --> 00:14:17.380
And when Anne came
on to the stage

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:20.610
and talked about what she
learned from Fred Rogers

00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:24.990
that she still uses as
a high level executive,

00:14:24.990 --> 00:14:27.080
it helped to crystallize
our feeling that there

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:31.220
are other people out there who
learned things from Fred that

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:35.540
stayed with them, not just
as my husband always says,

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:40.080
he helped you as a child, he
can help you as a grown up.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:45.670
So we went on and
we found a publisher

00:14:45.670 --> 00:14:50.620
and we pulled together
these three principles.

00:14:50.620 --> 00:14:52.262
Fred's lessons
were more profound

00:14:52.262 --> 00:14:54.470
than traditional methods of
management and leadership

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:55.290
training.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:57.640
He taught through
stories and fables.

00:14:57.640 --> 00:14:59.660
Those who watched
as children are now

00:14:59.660 --> 00:15:02.120
in middle and upper
management positions.

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.872
And here you are.

00:15:03.872 --> 00:15:05.330
You watched him
when you were a kid

00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:08.818
and now you're advancing
through your careers.

00:15:08.818 --> 00:15:12.280
IAN MITROFF: Can we go
through to the next slide?

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:15.970
Let me tell you what
crystallized is we went back

00:15:15.970 --> 00:15:18.750
and read the fables.

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:21.382
Seven principles
emerged early on.

00:15:21.382 --> 00:15:22.840
And those are the
seven principles.

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:24.160
Go to the next slide.

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:27.410
And each of them is illustrated
through a direct quote

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:30.309
from Fred and an accompanying
fable in the book.

00:15:30.309 --> 00:15:32.600
And we're going to read just
through the fables because

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:33.780
of time later.

00:15:33.780 --> 00:15:34.970
So the first one, connect.

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.510
You can read it.
"A person can grow

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:39.090
to his or her
fullest capacity only

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:42.000
in mutually caring
relationships with others."

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.490
Next please.

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:45.070
Concern.

00:15:45.070 --> 00:15:48.940
One of the misperceptions
of Fred Rogers

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:53.820
is that he was thoroughly
no rules, anything goes.

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:55.660
That's not true at all.

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:59.130
I think one of the best sayings
that we culled out from Fred

00:15:59.130 --> 00:16:02.990
is, "Setting rules," good
rules, not harsh rules,

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:05.480
"is one of the primary
ways in which we

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:07.470
show our love for others."

00:16:07.470 --> 00:16:11.220
Now, in a good organization
you do it with your employees,

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:14.000
not didactically, not
necessarily autocratically.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.200
Next one please.

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.290
"Play is the expression
of creativity,

00:16:19.290 --> 00:16:23.160
and I," Fred believes, "is at
the very root of our ability

00:16:23.160 --> 00:16:26.340
to learn to cope and
become whatever we may be."

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:28.470
Next please.

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:29.540
Communication.

00:16:29.540 --> 00:16:32.210
"In times of stress,"
especially in stress,

00:16:32.210 --> 00:16:34.010
"the best thing we
can do for each other

00:16:34.010 --> 00:16:35.660
is listen with our
ears and our hearts

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:37.368
to be assured that
our questions are just

00:16:37.368 --> 00:16:38.880
as important as our answers."

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.470
I don't need to tell you that
it's obviously broken down

00:16:41.470 --> 00:16:42.730
on our political life.

00:16:42.730 --> 00:16:45.760
One thing I ought to
say, we have no illusions

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:48.100
about what
organizations are today.

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:51.140
We're talking about an
ideal, which if we practice,

00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:54.500
it would hopefully improve
our organizations as they are.

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:56.580
Next one please.

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:57.730
Consciousness.

00:16:57.730 --> 00:17:00.860
"Take good care of that part of
you where your best dreams come

00:17:00.860 --> 00:17:04.957
from, that invisible part
of you," Fred was spiritual,

00:17:04.957 --> 00:17:07.290
"that allows you to look upon
yourself and your neighbor

00:17:07.290 --> 00:17:09.650
with delight."

00:17:09.650 --> 00:17:10.220
Next one.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:14.630
Maybe go back to
the previous one.

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:17.244
There is some growing
recognition, believe it or not,

00:17:17.244 --> 00:17:19.680
in business schools and
schools of management,

00:17:19.680 --> 00:17:23.900
that spirituality at work
plays a core role in our lives.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:25.970
I was fortunate to write
one of the earliest

00:17:25.970 --> 00:17:29.440
books on spirituality at
work, and I went around

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:32.170
and interviewed people
and what spirituality

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:33.810
meant to them during their day.

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:35.280
For example, how
much of themselves

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:36.321
they could bring to work?

00:17:36.321 --> 00:17:38.620
Next one, please.

00:17:38.620 --> 00:17:39.660
Courage.

00:17:39.660 --> 00:17:42.620
"One of the greatest paradoxes,"
about life, "about omnipotence

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:45.350
is that we need feel
it early in life,

00:17:45.350 --> 00:17:47.880
and lose it early
in life, in order

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:52.250
to achieve a healthy, realistic,
yet exciting sense of potency

00:17:52.250 --> 00:17:52.960
later on."

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:54.560
Next one, please.

00:17:54.560 --> 00:17:55.880
Community.

00:17:55.880 --> 00:17:58.160
"All of us, at some
time or other,"

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:00.250
I might say even
constantly, "need help.

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:03.006
Whether we're giving or
receiving help, each one of us

00:18:03.006 --> 00:18:05.172
has something valuable
to bring to the world.

00:18:05.172 --> 00:18:06.880
That's one of the
things that connects us

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:09.350
as neighbors-- in
our own way, each one

00:18:09.350 --> 00:18:10.600
is a giver and a receiver."

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:12.370
I mean if we could
summarize the book,

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:14.780
how could we turn
our organizations

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:17.180
at best into caring
neighborhoods.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:19.040
Next one, please.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:22.980
OK, here the seven
fables that we picked out

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:26.020
to illustrate each
of these principles.

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:29.260
And the fables just ring.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:31.590
In fact, they're really
in your consciences.

00:18:31.590 --> 00:18:34.100
Now, we're just going
to talk about two

00:18:34.100 --> 00:18:35.370
of them because of time.

00:18:35.370 --> 00:18:39.690
So Donna you ah-- We're going
to start with "Planet Purple"

00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:41.990
and we'll talk about "The
Bass Violin Festival."

00:18:41.990 --> 00:18:43.615
DONNA MITROFF: So
I'm going to give you

00:18:43.615 --> 00:18:46.350
a brief reading
of the story just

00:18:46.350 --> 00:18:49.280
to take you back
to remember what

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:52.950
happened in the story
of "Planet Purple."

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:57.620
And then you just think about
this as a mini case study,

00:18:57.620 --> 00:18:59.880
but Ian's going to
break it down or you

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:03.230
tell how it teaches
lessons for management

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:04.730
and for organizations.

00:19:04.730 --> 00:19:06.650
The story of "Planet Purple."

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:09.570
"On a space mission,
Lady Elaine Fairchilde

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:11.390
discovered a new planet.

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:14.350
A place where
everything was purple.

00:19:14.350 --> 00:19:16.620
Everyone had the
same purple home.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:18.160
The sky was purple.

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:20.720
The cars, chairs, and
streets were purple.

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:23.710
And there were the
same purple trees.

00:19:23.710 --> 00:19:25.800
In addition, all of
the boys and girls

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:28.210
were named Paul and Pauline.

00:19:28.210 --> 00:19:32.410
And every single panda
was call Purple Panda.

00:19:32.410 --> 00:19:36.710
Everyone on Planet Purple ate
purple pumpernickel pudding,

00:19:36.710 --> 00:19:39.980
and talked in the
same monotonous voice.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:42.270
And for years and
years, everybody

00:19:42.270 --> 00:19:45.800
dreamed the same dreams
and had the same hopes.

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:48.580
"When Lady Elaine Fairchilde's
bright green space

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:51.390
ship landed on Planet
Purple and she stepped out

00:19:51.390 --> 00:19:55.080
in her white astronaut suit,
the Planet Purple people

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:56.815
ran and hid in fear.

00:19:56.815 --> 00:20:00.930
But one Paul, and one
Pauline, and one purple panda

00:20:00.930 --> 00:20:02.390
didn't run and hide.

00:20:02.390 --> 00:20:05.550
They stayed around to look
at this curious creature.

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:08.000
Lady Elaine, whose favorite
color happened to be purple,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.580
was very intrigued
by this planet.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:12.550
She liked seeing
everything in purple

00:20:12.550 --> 00:20:14.110
and she liked not
having to remember

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:15.960
a lot of different names.

00:20:15.960 --> 00:20:18.250
"After exploring the
planet, she decided

00:20:18.250 --> 00:20:21.170
to fly back to tell
everyone back home

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:23.160
about this new planet.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:27.370
Lady Elaine didn't know that
Paul, Pauline, and Purple Panda

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:31.350
were watching her and
decided to follow her.

00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:33.840
"The Planet Purple
way to travel is just

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:36.310
by thinking and thinking alone.

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:38.780
All you have to do is
think that you're someplace

00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:40.740
and instantly you'll be there.

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:43.260
So Paul, Pauline,
and Purple Panda

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:46.510
thought about Lady Elaine, where
she was and immediately they

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:49.420
arrived in the Neighborhood
of Make Believe.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:52.290
"They could hardly believe
what they saw and heard.

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:55.270
Everything and
everybody was different.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:58.000
Purple Panda was so
excited that he sat down

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.120
in the first rocking
chair he saw.

00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:01.710
He rocked, and he
rocked, and rocked,

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:04.880
and then he remembered one
of Planet Purple's laws.

00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:07.660
Anyone who rocks
on a rocking chair

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:10.210
may not live in Planet Purple.

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:11.590
But now it was too late.

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:13.190
He could never go back.

00:21:13.190 --> 00:21:15.940
Paul and Pauline wanted
to explore this new place

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:16.880
before going back.

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:18.410
So they went everywhere.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:18.910
They looked.

00:21:18.910 --> 00:21:19.430
They listened.

00:21:19.430 --> 00:21:20.000
They smelled.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:20.620
They touched.

00:21:20.620 --> 00:21:23.170
They felt the colors,
They smelled the smells.

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:25.690
And they felt the
different feelings.

00:21:25.690 --> 00:21:28.820
"One day Paul fell
down and hurt himself.

00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:31.530
And he felt something wet
trickling down his cheek.

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:37.300
A rabbit asked him
why he was crying?

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:39.830
Paul had to ask
what crying meant.

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:42.340
No one ever cried
on Planet Purple.

00:21:42.340 --> 00:21:46.410
When the rabbit heard that Paul
had never cried before he said,

00:21:46.410 --> 00:21:48.590
you've just started to live.

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:50.560
"Finally, Paul and
Pauline decided

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:52.310
to return to Planet Purple.

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:54.210
So they use the
Planet Purple way

00:21:54.210 --> 00:21:57.620
to travel, thought about being
there and they were back home.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:00.640
They told the other Pauls
and Paulines about the place

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:02.020
where Lady Elaine lived.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:04.220
How everything is so
different and nobody

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:06.670
is exactly the same
as anyone else.

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:09.470
They even told about
Purple Panda rocking

00:22:09.470 --> 00:22:11.590
in the rocking
chair, and everyone

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:15.220
knew he'd broken the law
and could never come back.

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:18.320
"The other Pauls and
Paulines didn't like the idea

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:21.240
that everything and everybody
should be different.

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:25.580
Paul and Pauline helped them
imagine colors, sound, smells,

00:22:25.580 --> 00:22:26.480
feelings.

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:29.380
It took a long time to
change their planet.

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:31.840
And some people didn't
like some things,

00:22:31.840 --> 00:22:34.270
and other people didn't
like other things,

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:35.910
but everybody ended
up saying it was

00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:39.020
still better than being
the same all the time.

00:22:39.020 --> 00:22:42.050
They even changed the
law about rocking chairs

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:45.470
so Purple Panda could come
back any time he wanted.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:48.070
"The citizens of Planet
Purple held a celebration

00:22:48.070 --> 00:22:50.200
to announce that the
name of Planet Purple

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:54.060
would be changed to Planet
Purple Fairchilde in honor

00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:56.510
of the one who helped
them become different.

00:22:56.510 --> 00:22:59.990
Both Lady Elaine and Purple
Panda came to the celebration.

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:03.020
The End."

00:23:03.020 --> 00:23:08.890
Now just think about it for
a minute as a business case.

00:23:08.890 --> 00:23:10.650
I think you'll be surprised.

00:23:10.650 --> 00:23:11.880
Go ahead Ian.

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:14.410
IAN MITROFF: Here are some
of the principal lessons

00:23:14.410 --> 00:23:19.150
of Planet Purple translated into
the implications for business.

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:21.640
In many ways the fable
is about waking up

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:25.350
from an overly rigid,
hierarchical organization

00:23:25.350 --> 00:23:27.910
to a more equitable
organization.

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:31.180
Let me give you some things that
aren't up there on the slide.

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:33.850
Miss Fairchilde,
who could well be

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:38.530
an executive VP, her
challenging assignment

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:43.080
is explore different models for
the design of her organization.

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:45.860
She comes across
Planet Purple, Inc.

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:50.140
that has a beautiful simplicity,
but by just coming and asking

00:23:50.140 --> 00:23:54.530
questions, she's disturbed
the status quo profoundly.

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:57.430
When she comes across the
organization, as I said,

00:23:57.430 --> 00:24:00.870
it's an old fashioned, overly
repressed organization.

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:05.550
The employees are virtually in
a state of suspended, repressed

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:07.760
psychological and
emotional development.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:10.390
There's a lack of integration
between thinking and feelings.

00:24:10.390 --> 00:24:14.760
That's one of the main
underlying themes of the story.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:17.310
In effect, the people
live in a cocoon.

00:24:17.310 --> 00:24:20.250
Planet Purple organizations,
as we well know,

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:22.660
virtually have a single
measure of performance.

00:24:22.660 --> 00:24:24.930
All that matters
is the bottom line.

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:28.880
In contrast, Planet
Prism organizations

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:31.210
are a model of diversity.

00:24:31.210 --> 00:24:32.670
Everything is different.

00:24:32.670 --> 00:24:35.140
The King even enjoys--
the King Friday

00:24:35.140 --> 00:24:37.770
is the stand in for the
autocratic CEO-- even

00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:39.740
enjoys talking with employees.

00:24:39.740 --> 00:24:41.730
Yes, he's still in
charge because we're

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:43.810
not against hierarchy, per se.

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:45.060
That's not the point.

00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:48.190
But the point about the
Planet Prism organization,

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:52.140
their primary goal is do
no harm to the planet,

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:56.360
and make products that serve
authentic human needs, not

00:24:56.360 --> 00:24:57.980
false needs.

00:24:57.980 --> 00:24:59.916
