00:37:39.180 --> 00:37:41.990
And I'm wondering if you guys
have any insight in terms

00:37:41.990 --> 00:37:46.920
of Mr. Rogers' process on how
he got from what he wanted

00:37:46.920 --> 00:37:48.405
to get across and into a story.

00:37:48.405 --> 00:37:52.300
IAN MITROFF: David do you have
any idea what the process was

00:37:52.300 --> 00:37:53.850
that Fred went through?

00:37:53.850 --> 00:38:01.560
DAVID NEWELL: It was based a
lot on letters from the public.

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:03.710
This is not exactly
answering your question,

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:08.840
but the most requested topic
we ever had over the years

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:12.190
was from people
talking about Fred

00:38:12.190 --> 00:38:15.060
helping their
families with divorce.

00:38:15.060 --> 00:38:22.400
And we got so many-- and this
is going back maybe 20 years--

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:24.430
and Fred didn't
know how to do it.

00:38:24.430 --> 00:38:29.160
And finally-- he had a
professional child development

00:38:29.160 --> 00:38:32.190
expert with him all the
time-- and they finally

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:34.240
came up with a concept.

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:36.250
And we did a whole
week on divorce.

00:38:36.250 --> 00:38:38.570
And the one thing
that Fred wanted

00:38:38.570 --> 00:38:41.860
to get across to children was
that it's not their fault.

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:47.600
So it evolved like that.

00:38:47.600 --> 00:38:50.390
Another time, much
more light hearted,

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:54.560
there was a time when we
did a week on superheroes.

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:59.260
I had seen an article where a
child thought he was Superman,

00:38:59.260 --> 00:39:02.520
put a towel around his neck,
and jumped off a building,

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:03.360
and killed himself.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:04.920
And that was going on.

00:39:04.920 --> 00:39:07.770
And so we went to
"The Incredible Hulk,"

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:08.830
watching it being filmed.

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:10.390
Remember "The Incredible Hulk?"

00:39:10.390 --> 00:39:16.160
We went to Universal Studios
and showed that this is pretend.

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:18.010
Here's this person
getting into his makeup.

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:19.760
He broke it down.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.000
And Fred thought that way.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.850
He wanted to demystify a
lot of different things.

00:39:23.850 --> 00:39:27.420
But does that answer
your question?

00:39:27.420 --> 00:39:31.870
The creativity came a lot
of times from the public.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:36.050
But a lot, like "The
Bass Violin Festival."

00:39:36.050 --> 00:39:38.140
it came from Fred's
love of music, too.

00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:41.130
He used that as a metaphor of
sorts to get that point across.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:43.054
So it came from many
different places.

00:39:43.054 --> 00:39:44.220
Do you have anything to add?

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:48.220
IAN MITROFF: One other
response, the kind of philosophy

00:39:48.220 --> 00:39:51.240
I studied was really in the
school of pragmatism, William

00:39:51.240 --> 00:39:52.530
James.

00:39:52.530 --> 00:39:57.345
If you read the opening
pages of "Pragmatism", one

00:39:57.345 --> 00:40:00.640
of William James' key
works, he tells a story,

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:03.820
it's a brief story
about a working man, who

00:40:03.820 --> 00:40:05.440
had been out of work for a year.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:08.300
He finally got a job
in physical labor.

00:40:08.300 --> 00:40:09.210
But he was hurt.

00:40:09.210 --> 00:40:10.670
He was weak.

00:40:10.670 --> 00:40:13.080
He couldn't do it
so we came home.

00:40:13.080 --> 00:40:17.170
He killed his family
and he killed himself.

00:40:17.170 --> 00:40:20.180
And William James-- you know it
was ripped from the headlines--

00:40:20.180 --> 00:40:23.810
and William James asked
what does philosophy

00:40:23.810 --> 00:40:24.760
have to say to this?

00:40:24.760 --> 00:40:28.090
If it has nothing to say,
it has nothing to say.

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:30.590
And so the point
is, you know, I mean

00:40:30.590 --> 00:40:33.100
I've written scores of books.

00:40:33.100 --> 00:40:36.720
You've got wherever you
find the story-- I'm

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:38.790
working on a book
with my in-law,

00:40:38.790 --> 00:40:41.440
the father of my son-in-law.

00:40:41.440 --> 00:40:45.101
And he's a retired
bio-stat guy from Stanford.

00:40:45.101 --> 00:40:47.100
And we're talking about
writing a book on health

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:50.060
for the public, the kind
of concerns they have.

00:40:50.060 --> 00:40:54.290
He worked with Michael DeBakey
and I keep saying, Abe, we've

00:40:54.290 --> 00:40:56.410
got to crystallize the stories.

00:40:56.410 --> 00:40:59.800
For every point that
we want to make,

00:40:59.800 --> 00:41:02.240
there has to be an
accompanying story.

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:05.210
See one of things they didn't
say earlier about fables

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:06.730
and why we went with fables.

00:41:06.730 --> 00:41:09.760
The reason why
fables reverberate,

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:13.810
they're stereotypes, but
the good guys and bad guys

00:41:13.810 --> 00:41:15.330
are clearly drawn.

00:41:15.330 --> 00:41:17.720
That's why we were
drawn to fables.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:20.790
And the moral lessons are clear.

00:41:20.790 --> 00:41:22.340
Now you get into stereotype.

00:41:22.340 --> 00:41:23.530
You can exaggerate.

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:25.130
But that's what fables do.

00:41:25.130 --> 00:41:28.180
So they cut through
all the stuff there,

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:29.930
and they make it come to life.

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:31.310
They're human.

00:41:31.310 --> 00:41:32.705
And you don't get
that, you know?

00:41:32.705 --> 00:41:33.734
I mean come on.

00:41:33.734 --> 00:41:34.400
I'm an academic.

00:41:34.400 --> 00:41:36.483
I've been in the academic
world for my whole life.

00:41:36.483 --> 00:41:40.240
You're not rewarded
for doing that.

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:44.740
And there's so like all the
idea stuff, that's necessary.

00:41:44.740 --> 00:41:47.870
But it's not sufficient to
get it out here to the world.

00:41:47.870 --> 00:41:51.450
And that's why we wrote the book
because what a challenge for us

00:41:51.450 --> 00:41:53.310
to do what you were asking.

00:41:53.310 --> 00:41:54.060
Anybody else?

00:41:54.060 --> 00:41:55.230
We have a few minutes.

00:41:55.230 --> 00:41:58.015
Yes, sir.

00:41:58.015 --> 00:41:59.720
AUDIENCE: I think
it's a great concept

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:01.480
to apply these lessons
to the workplace.

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:04.510
Of course, you guys actually
shared the workplace

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:05.570
with Fred Rogers.

00:42:05.570 --> 00:42:08.340
I'm curious what was
that workplace like.

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:09.890
Was it any different?

00:42:09.890 --> 00:42:12.800
I loved your story of
actually closing your eyes.

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:14.290
Are there more
examples like that?

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:22.550
DONNA MITROFF: It was chaotic.

00:42:22.550 --> 00:42:26.640
It was always
bubbling and jumping

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:29.420
and things were happening and
things didn't get done on time.

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.310
Some recognition up here.

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:37.990
But there was always that
underlying current of we

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:39.960
know where we're going.

00:42:39.960 --> 00:42:42.480
This is about
something important.

00:42:42.480 --> 00:42:46.180
And that's the thing that kept
everybody coming back together.

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:48.410
Now the day-to-day stories?

00:42:48.410 --> 00:42:50.510
David has piles of those.

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:52.510
DAVID NEWELL: I was in
every one of the tapings.

00:42:52.510 --> 00:42:56.960
We did over thousands of
tapings and I was in them a lot.

00:42:56.960 --> 00:43:00.730
And the one time that you could
tell-- Fred was a musician--

00:43:00.730 --> 00:43:04.790
and you could tell
when he was frustrated.

00:43:04.790 --> 00:43:07.900
He would never yell or throw
a sneaker across the floor.

00:43:07.900 --> 00:43:09.680
He would go to the piano.

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:12.000
And when we sat
down at the piano

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:15.600
and would play the piano
that was his-- anger

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:18.490
came out through his
fingers or his frustrations.

00:43:18.490 --> 00:43:19.860
And that's how he dealt with it.

00:43:19.860 --> 00:43:21.510
And people would
follow that, too.

00:43:21.510 --> 00:43:24.350
They knew that Fred
was saying something

00:43:24.350 --> 00:43:26.480
to them when the
piano would start.

00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:30.470
And after every taping
Fred had a tradition,

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:32.350
he'd go to the piano
and-- you're all

00:43:32.350 --> 00:43:35.090
too young to know up it, but in
the movie theaters in the '40s

00:43:35.090 --> 00:43:37.500
and '50s, they had newsreels.

00:43:37.500 --> 00:43:39.820
And there was a news
reel that started out

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:41.670
with a rooster crowing.

00:43:41.670 --> 00:43:43.900
It as the RKO Warner
Brothers News,

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:47.110
something that had a
very distinct theme.

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:48.530
Da, da, da dat da da.

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:51.770
It's like playing "And That's
All Folks" from Looney Tunes.

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:54.850
He would sit down and play that,
and we knew the day was done.

00:43:54.850 --> 00:43:57.510
But Fred talked through music.

00:43:57.510 --> 00:43:59.389
DONNA MITROFF: He talked
through music, yeah.

00:43:59.389 --> 00:44:01.180
IAN MITROFF: One thing
that I do remember--

00:44:01.180 --> 00:44:03.670
I'll get the story a little
bit wrong, not exactly.

00:44:03.670 --> 00:44:07.080
I remember watching Fred one
time on the old "Johnny Carson

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:07.580
Show."

00:44:07.580 --> 00:44:10.390
I don't how many of you watched
the old "Johnny Carson Show."

00:44:10.390 --> 00:44:13.530
And Fred was talking
about what he did.

00:44:13.530 --> 00:44:16.010
Johnny, they were
engaged in conversation.

00:44:16.010 --> 00:44:19.520
And Fred was talking about
the importance of children's

00:44:19.520 --> 00:44:22.480
feelings, and somebody
in the audience guffawed.

00:44:22.480 --> 00:44:25.720
And Fred looked at that
person steely cold and said,

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:27.600
that's not funny.

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:29.420
And I remember that
because, again,

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:33.170
to think that OK, he was
bubbly and light all the time.

00:44:33.170 --> 00:44:33.990
No way.

00:44:33.990 --> 00:44:36.580
I mean, yes, this
was a spiritual,

00:44:36.580 --> 00:44:38.360
a really good person.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:40.390
But the things that
he didn't have strong

00:44:40.390 --> 00:44:43.220
values-- In fact, we
talked about that.

00:44:43.220 --> 00:44:46.420
This was more than a
one time occurrence.

00:44:46.420 --> 00:44:50.810
I know when I've
been involved-- I'm

00:44:50.810 --> 00:44:53.400
in a research
center at Berkeley--

00:44:53.400 --> 00:44:56.970
and we have people come in and
they'll talk about feelings--

00:44:56.970 --> 00:44:59.930
because it's a center about
crises and everything--

00:44:59.930 --> 00:45:02.140
they'll talk about warm fuzzies.

00:45:02.140 --> 00:45:05.380
I have to bite my tongue
and I can't always do it.

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:08.540
And say, don't you
insult feelings that way.

00:45:08.540 --> 00:45:10.124
You don't do that with a kid.

00:45:10.124 --> 00:45:11.415
DONNA MITROFF: Or with anybody.

00:45:11.415 --> 00:45:11.690
IAN MITROFF: Or with anybody.

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:13.770
DONNA MITROFF: Because
you bring those feelings

00:45:13.770 --> 00:45:16.860
with you no matter what.

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:19.200
And they have to be dealt
with no matter where you are,

00:45:19.200 --> 00:45:21.230
no matter what age you are,
they have to be dealt with.

00:45:21.230 --> 00:45:22.813
IAN MITROFF: One of
the things I found

00:45:22.813 --> 00:45:25.020
when I did my book on
spiritually was called

00:45:25.020 --> 00:45:27.360
"The Spiritual Audit
of Corporate America,"

00:45:27.360 --> 00:45:30.130
that one of the things
that people talk about what

00:45:30.130 --> 00:45:32.760
spirituality meant
to them at work

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:34.330
was how much of
their whole person

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:35.371
they could bring to work.

00:45:35.371 --> 00:45:37.260
Could they only bring
their head, but not

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:39.780
your their feelings, their
heart, and their body.

00:45:39.780 --> 00:45:43.190
And so the whole point is, we're
fragmented enough in our lives

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:45.560
that they didn't want to be
further fragmented at work.

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:48.180
Or to go home and repair
for all the beating

00:45:48.180 --> 00:45:49.726
up that they took
during the week.

00:45:49.726 --> 00:45:51.850
And then go home and repair
so they could come back

00:45:51.850 --> 00:45:54.230
and take another
40, 50 hours more.

00:45:54.230 --> 00:45:57.870
So the organizations that quote
have a spiritual bent, whatever

00:45:57.870 --> 00:46:01.020
you want to call it, get
more of the whole person.

00:46:01.020 --> 00:46:03.600
They don't exploit that person.

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:05.640
And they get more
of the creativity.

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:08.980
That's why all of these
fables really reverberate.

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:10.966
OK, I think we
have time for more.

00:46:10.966 --> 00:46:12.590
DONNA MITROFF: Do we
any time Courtney?

00:46:12.590 --> 00:46:13.756
COURTNEY: One more question.

00:46:13.756 --> 00:46:17.010
DAVID NEWELL: Can I follow
up with what you asked?

00:46:17.010 --> 00:46:19.070
This just shows
Fred's sense of humor.

00:46:19.070 --> 00:46:22.190
He had a wonderful
sense of humor.

00:46:22.190 --> 00:46:23.130
The crew knew this.

00:46:23.130 --> 00:46:25.950
You know how he changed
his shoes and sneakers

00:46:25.950 --> 00:46:27.310
and put his--?

00:46:27.310 --> 00:46:29.160
At the very end of
the program, they

00:46:29.160 --> 00:46:32.800
snuck in a pair
of smaller shoes.

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:36.170
And he put his shoe on
by talking and winding

00:46:36.170 --> 00:46:37.010
his foot into it.

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:37.990
And he couldn't do it.

00:46:37.990 --> 00:46:39.330
And he couldn't do it.

00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:41.650
And you heard the
crew started to laugh.

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:46.470
He wore a size 10, and
they gave him size 8.

00:46:46.470 --> 00:46:48.470
You can't tell just
by looking at it.

00:46:48.470 --> 00:46:51.970
And he thought
that was so funny.

00:46:51.970 --> 00:46:55.980
And it Dick Clark showed
it on his outtake reels.

00:46:55.980 --> 00:46:58.500
Just one other quicky.

00:46:58.500 --> 00:47:01.110
You know those blow up dolls?

00:47:01.110 --> 00:47:03.830
This is something that nobody's
ever told anyone, but I will.

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:06.347
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:06.347 --> 00:47:08.430
They said, OK, Fred, we're
going to start to show.

00:47:08.430 --> 00:47:10.346
He came in, sang the
song, put the sweater on,

00:47:10.346 --> 00:47:12.480
went to the cupboard,
and there was a blow up

00:47:12.480 --> 00:47:15.010
doll hanging in the closet.

00:47:15.010 --> 00:47:16.550
And it startled him.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:22.607
So he pulled it out and
started dancing with it.

00:47:22.607 --> 00:47:24.440
DONNA MITROFF: That was
a creative solution.

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:25.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:27.260
DAVID NEWELL: But
that was an outtake

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:29.730
that we never let
out of our hands.

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:31.170
But you now know about it.

00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:37.250
But the point I'm saying is
that he had a sense of humor.

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:39.670
And it goes back
to feelings, too.

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:42.390
He wasn't mad and stomped
out and said, OK, you're

00:47:42.390 --> 00:47:43.670
all suspended.

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:47.130
That didn't work with Fred.

00:47:47.130 --> 00:47:48.380
AUDIENCE: Just a comment.

00:47:48.380 --> 00:47:51.010
There's been a lot of
attention in the media

00:47:51.010 --> 00:47:54.270
lately about women taking
on management positions

00:47:54.270 --> 00:47:57.100
and doing very well,
exercising more,

00:47:57.100 --> 00:47:59.920
kind of, masculine management
type characteristics.

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:01.490
But the thing that
I love about Fred,

00:48:01.490 --> 00:48:03.281
and especially looking
back because I never

00:48:03.281 --> 00:48:06.290
would have picked this up as a
child, but as an adult, is he

00:48:06.290 --> 00:48:09.370
was one of the first men who
was comfortable exhibiting

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:11.010
more feminine characteristics.

00:48:11.010 --> 00:48:13.430
As a man, being in
touch with feelings.

00:48:13.430 --> 00:48:16.730
DONNA MITROFF: And he also
created Lady Elaine Fairchilde.

00:48:16.730 --> 00:48:17.305
And she--

00:48:17.305 --> 00:48:18.263
AUDIENCE: There you go.

00:48:18.263 --> 00:48:21.050
DONNA MITROFF: --was
that futuristic woman,

00:48:21.050 --> 00:48:23.210
who wasn't afraid to stand up.

00:48:23.210 --> 00:48:25.740
There are other
stories in our book

00:48:25.740 --> 00:48:29.390
where she was the one
who stood up to the CEO

00:48:29.390 --> 00:48:32.640
and said, don't ask me to do
something if you don't tell me

00:48:32.640 --> 00:48:33.850
why I'm going to do it.

00:48:33.850 --> 00:48:37.140
I mean that's pretty
masculine but that was--

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:39.190
IAN MITROFF: Suzanne,
I have to talk

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:42.070
about, you raised something
that's really important.

00:48:42.070 --> 00:48:46.610
One of the things about
Fred, which is sad,

00:48:46.610 --> 00:48:49.130
is that many men
are uncomfortable.

00:48:49.130 --> 00:48:51.330
So you have all
these urban legends

00:48:51.330 --> 00:48:54.340
that underneath he was
tattooed, and he was a seal,

00:48:54.340 --> 00:48:56.830
and all that kind of
stuff because the reason

00:48:56.830 --> 00:49:02.480
is you couldn't take that there
would be a man who would openly

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:05.280
talk about feelings, and
wouldn't be a effeminate--

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:08.090
or whatever the derogatory
term of the day-- and we

00:49:08.090 --> 00:49:09.750
know all that kind of stuff.

00:49:09.750 --> 00:49:16.030
So they had to project onto Fred
their fears and anxiety to make

00:49:16.030 --> 00:49:18.710
him into something
that he wasn't.

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:21.100
He was masculine.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:25.120
But I mean if you talk about,
if you go to Jung, where

00:49:25.120 --> 00:49:28.540
you have both the feminine
and the masculine archetypes.

00:49:28.540 --> 00:49:30.750
They are in every one of
us, but they're not always

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:31.690
equally developed.

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:34.430
And we're not always equally
comfortable in displaying

00:49:34.430 --> 00:49:35.510
both of them.

00:49:35.510 --> 00:49:39.270
